<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>7.3 Liter Diesel Engine Service (1991) - CYLINDER HEAD AND VALVES - CYLINDER HEAD (Reconditioning) - STEEL
        (SEAL) BALLS
    </stitle>
    <svcman/>
    <svcproc svcproctype="proctype" graphiccount="5">
        <title>STEEL (SEAL) BALLS</title>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Inspection</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Visually inspect seal balls for evidence of leakage (rust, small cracks or wetness).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove and install seal balls as inspection warrants.</para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Each cylinder head contains four 13/32 in. steel (seal) balls located in passage holes on
                            the exhaust manifold side of the cylinder head. The balls seal coolant flow through the
                            cross drilled passages which provide positive coolant flow to the valve seat areas (Figure
                            <hotlnk xrefid="ef4350329">3.29</hotlnk>).
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="ef4350328" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg12327a" filename="../figcg1/CG12327A.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3.28 Installing Cylinder Head Core Plugs</caption>
                </figure>
                <figure id="ef4350329" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic id="cg11495" filename="../figcg1/CG11495.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3.29 Crossdrilled Passages in Cylinder Head (Bottom View)</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Removal</title>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>Cylinder head steel (seal) balls should not be disturbed unless evidence of leakage exists.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Fabricate a seal ball removal tool as follows: (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4350330">3.30</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Using a 1/4 in. Allen wrench, cut or grind the "J" bend so a 3/4 in. protrusion is
                        present.
                    </para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Weld either a square or round piece of bar stock to the Allen wrench, forming a tee
                        handle.
                    </para>
                </step2>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert the "J" bend of the remover tool into the orifice in the cylinder head, where the
                    ball is to be removed. Apply downward pressure to the "tee" handle and the ball will pop out (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4350331">3.31</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Cleaning</title>
            <para>If ball(s) are removed, clean passage(s) with a suitable brush and blow out with filtered compressed
                air.
            </para>
        </svcsubproc>
        <svcsubproc>
            <title>Installation</title>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install a new 13/32 in. steel (seal) ball as follows: (
                    <emph type="bold">Figure
                        <hotlnk xrefid="ef4350332">3.32</hotlnk>
                    </emph>
                    ).
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <important>
                        <para>TO PREVENT CYLINDER HEAD CRACKING, DO NOT ATTEMPT TO INSTALL A LARGER DIAMETER STEEL
                            (SEAL) BALL THAN SPECIFIED.
                        </para>
                    </important>
                </specpara>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Place new ball over orifice at side of cylinder head.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Apply Loctite&#8482; hydraulic sealant to ball.</para>
                </step2>
                <step2>
                    <para count="1">Using a punch and hammer, drive ball into orifice until seated.</para>
                    <figure id="ef4350330" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11493" filename="../figcg1/CG11493.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3.30 Fabricate Seal Ball Remover Tool</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef4350331" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg11494" filename="../figcg1/CG11494.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3.31 Remove Steel (Seal) Ball</caption>
                    </figure>
                    <figure id="ef4350332" figsize="col-wide">
                        <graphic id="cg12069" filename="../figcg1/CG12069.webp" type="webp"/>
                        <caption>Figure 3.32 Installing a New Steel (Seal) Ball</caption>
                    </figure>
                </step2>
            </step1>
        </svcsubproc>
    </svcproc>
